    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIn a previous version of neovim, fold regions defined by tree-sitter were working nicely reliably.\n\nIn current version, any newly-opened file that is supposed to be using tree-sitter for folding has no folding regions at all. For these files, I have `foldmethod=expr foldexpr=nvim_treesitter#foldexpr()`. (For some file types, such as `.py`, I have `foldmethod=indent` and these are working fine).\n\nFor example, I open a 100-ish line `.c` file. I have `foldcolumn` set to 2, but none are shown there. None of the fold commands take effect. I can hit `i` to enter insert mode and add more text, no change. I hit `u` to undo that change, and instantly all the folding regions from the line my edit was made on until the end of the file suddenly appear (though, any regions that should have begun in previous lines only in fact start on this line). Those regions are now somewhat stable during further edits. Other commands like `o` to open a new line will also add folding regions from here until end-of-file. If I then `:e` to reload the file from disk, all the fold regions disappear and I'm now left with nothing again. If I now `:e another-file.c` that new file loads in a new buffer, with no regions. I can `:bn` to cycle between them one time and no folds appear. If I `:bn` a second time then suddenly all the folds appear.\n\nGiven that folds sometimes work and can be unreliably triggered into working, I believe that all the actual tree-sitter folding definitions and parsing are happening correctly, and this bug relates to when the tree-sitter folding queries are being run and updated into the buffer state.\n\nIn summary: it feels like tree-sitter fold regions are not being updated into the buffer at all of the correct times for doing so.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nnvim demo.c\n:set fdc=2\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nFold regions should be defined and visible in the fold column.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.11.6\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nUnable to test; vim does not use tree-sitter\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux debian/testing\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\npangoterm\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm\n\n### Installation\n\nDebian/testing",
